      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nNearly half of the metals cataloged in the NIST SRD-46 database have very sparse (or zero) stability-constant data. Many of these are exotic oxidation states (e.g., Cr⁴⁺, Mo⁵⁺, Pb⁴⁺), transactinides (No²⁺, Md³⁺, Fm³⁺), organometallic species (Ph₃Sn⁺, Bu₃Pb⁺), or noble-gas/non-metal entries (He, O) that are rarely studied in aqueous equilibrium chemistry. This highlights how unevenly experimental effort is distributed across the periodic table — a handful of common metals like Cu²⁺, Ni²⁺, and Zn²⁺ dominate the measurement landscape while the long tail of rare species remains data-poor.\n\n*Source: NIST Standard Reference Database 46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes).*",
